5|$|In {{some areas}} of Nigeria, ethnic groups speak more than one language. The <b>official</b> <b>language</b> of Nigeria, English, was chosen to {{facilitate}} the cultural and linguistic unity of the country, owing {{to the influence of}} British colonisation that ended in 1960.|$|E
50|$|Two of Canada's {{northern}} territories legislate {{a variety}} of Indigenous languages. Nunavut holds Inuktitut and Inuinnaqtun as <b>official</b> <b>languages,</b> and Northwest Territories has nine <b>official</b> <b>languages</b> aside from English and French: Cree, Dënesųłiné, Gwich’in, Inuinnaqtun, Inuktitut, Inuvialuktun, North and South Slavey and Tłı̨chǫ. As these <b>official</b> <b>languages</b> are legislated at a territorial (sub-federal) level, they can be construed as national languages.|$|R
